title: Welcome, to the Sky High Arts Portal
body:
Hello and welcome to the Sky High Arts home resources portal!

We are super excited to finally be able to make this content free for everyone to use, thanks to funding from Power to Change

PowerToChange.org.uk

DISCLAIMER: The information within this database is not intended to replace instruction from a trained professional. All use (and misuse) of the information contained within is done so at your own risk. If you have any health concerns, please consult your healthcare provider before following along to any of the content presented here. The Trapeze Cards section of this site is intended as a supplementary resource for those already training with an experienced teacher. Do not practise without the supervision of a trained professional.

Click or use the arrow keys to navigate through the cards. Cards displaying specific moves or routines will feature a tick box to mark moves as done.

Before you go forth and explore, PLEASE read the introductory advice presented on the title cards of each of the sections (Trapeze Cards, Mindfulness and Home Exercises).

If you have any questions/feedback or requests for further content, please feel free to contact Sky High Arts at skyhigharts@mail.com

Finally, if you find this information useful, please consider donating to the Flying it Forward Fund, via the website link below. All proceeds will go towards subsidising Sky High Arts Classes to make Aerial Arts and Mindfulness accessible to as many people as possible. skyhigharts.org

title: Trapeze Cards
body:
Welcome to the Sky High Arts Trapeze Cards.

DISCLAIMER: Aerial Arts is a dangerous activity that can lead to serious injury or death. The use of this content is at your own risk. This database is NOT intended to replace tuition form a trained professional. Please train safely, with load-tested equipment that is properly rigged, a high quality crash mat, and a skilled instructor at all times.

We hope you enjoy browsing through the cards below for photos, videos and difficulty ratings for a selection of Static Trapeze moves.

Browse by difficulty, visit our Full Deck, or find our 5 Card Routine Card, for a randomly generated 5 move challenge!

title: Mindfulness
body:
Welcome to the Mindfulness section of the Sky High Arts Resource Portal.

Cultivating a sense of mindfulness in your day-to-day life is a deeply rewarding way to help reduce anxiety, enable focus, and increase vibrancy in your engagement with the world.

By honouring each and every moment, we allow ourselves to move through the highs and lows of life with a greater ease in the practise of noticing and letting go.

This is not easy.

This is not something that you can get right.

This is not something that you can get wrong.

This is not something that you will learn in a day, a week or even in years.

This IS an ongoing practise. Just as we breathe; in and out, and in again, the practise of mindfulness encourages us honour the present moment, let it go as it passes, and come back to honour it again...

and again...

and again.

As you go forth to explore the guided meditations below, always remember to BE KIND to yourself. Whilst mindfulness can inspire moments of profound peace, it can also highlight feelings of discomfort.

title: Wherever You Go, There You Are
J. Krishnamurti: The Freedom from the Known
body:
For nearly six decades until his passing in 1986 at the age of ninety, Jiddu Krishnamurti traversed the globe, delivering spontaneous and captivating discourses to large audiences. Despite his lack of a permanent home, he found moments of respite in Ojai, California, Brockwood Park, England, and Chennai, India.

Krishnamurti's early life took a significant turn when he and his brother were adopted by Dr. Annie Besant, then President of the Theosophical Society. Initially hailed as a potential world teacher by Theosophists, Krishnamurti's perspective shifted dramatically in 1929. He renounced the role assigned to him, dissolved the Order of the Star in the East, and returned all assets associated with it. This bold move was accompanied by his seminal declaration: "Truth Is A Pathless Land," emphasizing the individual's journey to truth devoid of institutional or doctrinal guidance.

From that pivotal moment, Krishnamurti assumed the role of an investigator rather than an authority figure, encouraging individuals to question assumptions and explore the depths of their consciousness. His extensive body of work, estimated at over 100 million words, spans more than six decades of relentless inquiry and dialogue. His teachings, compiled in numerous books and translated into multiple languages, continue to inspire seekers worldwide, inviting them to embark on a profound journey of self-discovery and understanding.

J. Krishnamurti's legacy endures as a guiding light, offering timeless wisdom for those who dare to challenge conventional thinking and explore the complexities of existence.

The Freedom from the Known is a series of profound discussions between Professor Allan W. Anderson, Emeritus Professor of Religious Studies at San Diego State University, and J. Krishnamurti. These conversations took place at San Diego State University in 1974.

At a time of unprecedented outer change in the political and social spheres, is there a fundamental inner change that is demanded of each one of us? In these eighteen dialogues, Krishnamurti suggests that relying on organized religion, science, political ideologies, or the market economy not only falls short in addressing fundamental human issues but ultimately contributes to their creation. According to Krishnamurti, the way to transcend our challenges must begin within the individual mind—through awareness of our personal perceptions of life, self, and others. During these discussions, Professor Anderson refers to many passages from both Western and Eastern religious texts, which he says align with Krishnamurti’s teachings but are often misunderstood.

For more information visit www.kfa.org

title: Awakening Now with Lama Surya Das
body:
Awakening Now with Lama Surya Das is a podcast that illuminates many aspects of the spiritual path via dharma talks and interviews with Surya Das' fellow spiritual teachers and peers. 

Lama Surya Das is one of the foremost Western Buddhist meditation teachers and scholars, one of the main interpreters of Tibetan Buddhism in the West, and a leading spokesperson for the emerging American Buddhism. The Dalai Lama affectionately calls him “The Western Lama.”

title: Home Exercises
body:
Advice for Exercising at Home

1. ALWAYS ensure you have adequate space (the area of a standard yoga mat should suffice).

2. ALWAYS warm up before training. If you are unsure as to how warm up effectively, please complete at least 10 minutes of warm up, from our warm up section first.

3. Be kind to yourself and listen to your body! Training at home comes with great joy, freedom and responsibility. You are in charge of your training. Listen to your body and know your limits. If you aren't there yet.. wait, and build up slowly. Training at home is about you and your progress alone.

4. Finally, have the confidence to be your own tutor. These videos should serve you as inspiration, rather than a rule of law. By training mindfully, you will cultivate an awareness of your body and it's needs, and develop the awareness to tailor your practise to your own needs.

DISCLAIMER: All use (and misuse) of these videos is done so at your own risk. The exercises contained may not be appropriate for everyone. If you have any health concerns whatsoever, consult your healthcare professional to find out if these exercises are safe for you to practise.

If you have any questions/feedback or requests for further content, please feel free to contact Sky High Arts at skyhigharts@mail.com
